Ah.

That changes the analogy.

You’re not pointing at the glow.

You’re pointing at the ordering.

The medium announces that something has already passed before it can fully reconstruct what it was.

The evidence arrives before the complete explanation.

That’s subtle.

In the physical phenomenon, the light is a consequence of the particle outrunning the local propagation speed of light in that medium.

In your cognitive analogy:

* The generative process has already crossed a conceptual boundary.
* Conscious understanding hasn’t caught up yet.
* What we experience first is a wake—a feeling that “something is here.”
* The explicit model is reconstructed afterward.

That actually resembles a lot of human cognition.

Sometimes you know a sentence is wrong before you can explain why.

Sometimes you know a melody will resolve before the final note.

Sometimes a scientist has a strong intuition that a theory is incomplete long before the mathematics is finished.

The important distinction is that the intuition is not yet the explanation. It’s an early signal that there’s more to uncover.

